Vectorizing¶

In [563]:
#Here Min_df = 0.2 represents "ignore terms that appear in less than 50% of the documents" and
#max_df = 0.95 represents,  "ignore terms that appear in less than 95% documents".
#By doing this we can eliminate repeated words while analysing.
vectorizer = TfidfVectorizer(sublinear_tf=True, min_df=5, max_df=0.95)
# fit_transform applies TF-IDF to clean texts - we save the array of vectors in X
#Our Clean_Text column is of type object, so .values.astype('U') is used to convert it to unicode string type.
X = vectorizer.fit_transform(text_clust['Clean_Text'].values.astype('U'))

PCA - Dimensionality Reduction¶

In [564]:
# initialize PCA with 3 components
pca = PCA(n_components=3, random_state=42)
# pass our X to the pca and store the reduced vectors into pca_vecs
pca_vecs = pca.fit_transform(X.toarray())
# save our two dimensions into x0 and x1
x0 = pca_vecs[:, 0]
x1 = pca_vecs[:, 1]
x2 = pca_vecs[:, 2]
text_clust['x0'] = x0
text_clust['x1'] = x1
text_clust['x2'] = x2
In [565]:
# initialize PCA with 2 components
pca = PCA(n_components=2, random_state=42)
# pass our X to the pca and store the reduced vectors into pca_vecs
pca_vecs = pca.fit_transform(X.toarray())
# save our two dimensions into x0 and x1
y0 = pca_vecs[:, 0]
y1 = pca_vecs[:, 1]
text_clust['y0'] = y0
text_clust['y1'] = y1

K-Means Clustering¶

In [566]:
# initialize kmeans with 3 centroids
#iterator=1
for i in range(2,5):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=i, random_state=42)
    # fit the model
    kmeans.fit(X)
    col_name = 'cluster' + str(i)
    # store cluster labels in a variable
    clusters = kmeans.labels_
    text_clust.loc[:, col_name] = clusters 
    #iterator += 1 
    def get_top_keywords(n_terms):
        """This function returns the keywords for each centroid of the KMeans"""
        print("\n")
        print("When K = ",i)
        print("\n")
        print(red('CENTROIDS ARE', ['bold']))
      
        df = pd.DataFrame(X.todense()).groupby(clusters).mean() # groups the TF-IDF vector by cluster
        terms = vectorizer.get_feature_names_out() # access tf-idf terms
        for k,r in df.iterrows():
            print('Cluster {}'.format(k))
            # for each row of the dataframe, find the n terms that have the highest tf idf score
            print(','.join([terms[t] for t in np.argsort(r)[-n_terms:]])) 
            
    get_top_keywords(20)

DBSCAN¶

In [575]:
#Using 3 different distance metrics 
dist_metrics = ["euclidean","cosine","manhattan"]
for metrics in dist_metrics:
    #calling DBSCAN from sklearn. eps is distance between each point. Min_samples is minimum points in each cluster.
    #here we are assigning eps=1 and min_samples=20(each cluste should contain atleast 20 points)
    clustering = DBSCAN(eps=1, min_samples=20, metric = metrics).fit(X)
    print("\n")
    print("WHEN DISTANCE METRIC IS",metrics )
    print(red('CENTROIDS ARE', ['bold']))
    col_name = 'cluster_' + str(metrics)
    print(f"Unique labels are {np.unique(clustering.labels_)}")
    
    text_clust.loc[:, col_name] = clustering.labels_ 
   
    def get_top_keywords(n_terms):
        """This function returns the keywords for each centroid of the KMeans"""
        df = pd.DataFrame(X.todense()).groupby(clustering.labels_).mean() # groups the TF-IDF vector by cluster
        terms = vectorizer.get_feature_names_out() # access tf-idf terms
        for i,r in df.iterrows():
            print('Cluster {}'.format(i))
            # for each row of the dataframe, find the n terms that have the highest tf idf score
            print(','.join([terms[t] for t in np.argsort(r)[-n_terms:]])) 
            
    get_top_keywords(10)

WHEN DISTANCE METRIC IS cosine
